"Abstract The Clinton administration is proposing sweeping changes to the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) of 1966 to accommodate the protection of a new category of information designated ‘Critical Infrastructure Information Protected’ or, in its shortened form, ‘CII Protected’. The proposed changes to the FOIA, which was originally enacted to give Americans greater access to government information, were drawn up jointly by Richard Clarke, the President’s National Coordinator for Security, Infrastructure Protection, and Counter_Terrorism, and officials of the Department of Justice. Efforts to change the FOIA arose from industry concerns that unless there were statutory protections, companies would be reluctant to voluntarily share information on specific security weaknesses and vulnerabilities within their own infrastructures with the government."
